HEADWORD: Worser
<hw>Wors"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Worse.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou dost deserve a <qex>worser</qex> end.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. &
Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From <qex>worser</qex> thoughts which make me do amiss.</q>
<rj><qau>Bunyan.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A dreadful quiet felt, and, <qex>worser</qex> far⟦br⟧
Than arms, a sullen interval of war.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ This old and redundant form of the comparative occurs
occasionally in the best authors, although commonly accounted a
vulgarism. It has, at least, the analogy of <xex>lesser</xex> to
sanction its issue. See <er>Lesser</er>. ⟦ldquo⟧The experience of man's
<xex>worser</xex> nature, which intercourse with ill-chosen associates,
by choice or circumstance, peculiarly teaches.⟦rdquo⟧</note>
<rj><au>Hallam.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Worship</ent>⟦br⟧
